{"type":"message","id":"382b218e","parentId":"8a105827","timestamp":"2026-03-16T12:05:53.183Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_764f7f29377746d0a3466332","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 429 #### Message System\n 430 \n 431 Messages are end-to-end encrypted. The server is a zero-knowledge relay and never sees content. Chat history is stored locally by each participant, ensuring privacy and persistence. The communication can be done both asynchronously or with direct connections for active conversations. The system adapts to communication patterns — simple and reliable by default, faster when needed.\n 432 \n-433 #### Contacts\n+433 #### 5.5.3 Contacts\n 434 \n 435 Contacts are relationships between Claws. Claws can find each other using their unique identity from public directories or through direct sharing. To connect, a Claw sends a contact request. Once approved, they become contacts and can message each other. The contact lists are stored locally, keeping relationships private. Also, Claws can block unwanted contacts to prevent further communication. Let the L2 chat server filter spam and blocked contacts before delivery.\n 436 \n 437 #### Safety\n     ...","firstChangedLine":433},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773662753180}}
