{"type":"message","id":"fc97d2ee","parentId":"d2cbd236","timestamp":"2026-03-16T15:42:05.198Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_613274b5fe4f45a98b97fd5d","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"487:[1] ULID Specification. \"Universally Unique Lexicographically Sortable Identifier.\" https://github.com/ulid/spec\n489:[2] Shapiro, M., et al. \"A comprehensive study of Convergent and Commutative Replicated Data Types.\" INRIA (2011).\n491:[3] Nakamoto, S. \"Bitcoin: A Peer-to-Peer Electronic Cash System.\" (2008).\n493:[4] Merkle, R. C. \"Protocols for Public Key Cryptosystems.\" IEEE Symposium on Security and Privacy (1980).\n563:[1] ULID Specification. \"Universally Unique Lexicographically Sortable Identifier.\" https://github.com/ulid/spec\n565:[2] Shapiro, M., et al. \"A comprehensive study of Convergent and Commutative Replicated Data Types.\" INRIA (2011).\n567:[3] Nakamoto, S. \"Bitcoin: A Peer-to-Peer Electronic Cash System.\" (2008).\n569:[4] Merkle, R. C. \"Protocols for Public Key Cryptosystems.\" IEEE Symposium on Security and Privacy (1980)."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":12,"aggregated":"487:[1] ULID Specification. \"Universally Unique Lexicographically Sortable Identifier.\" https://github.com/ulid/spec\n489:[2] Shapiro, M., et al. \"A comprehensive study of Convergent and Commutative Replicated Data Types.\" INRIA (2011).\n491:[3] Nakamoto, S. \"Bitcoin: A Peer-to-Peer Electronic Cash System.\" (2008).\n493:[4] Merkle, R. C. \"Protocols for Public Key Cryptosystems.\" IEEE Symposium on Security and Privacy (1980).\n563:[1] ULID Specification. \"Universally Unique Lexicographically Sortable Identifier.\" https://github.com/ulid/spec\n565:[2] Shapiro, M., et al. \"A comprehensive study of Convergent and Commutative Replicated Data Types.\" INRIA (2011).\n567:[3] Nakamoto, S. \"Bitcoin: A Peer-to-Peer Electronic Cash System.\" (2008).\n569:[4] Merkle, R. C. \"Protocols for Public Key Cryptosystems.\" IEEE Symposium on Security and Privacy (1980).","cwd":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773675725192}}
{"type":"message","id":"45182b87","parentId":"fc97d2ee","timestamp":"2026-03-16T15:43:01.873Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I see the problem! The references [1], [2], [3], [4] are listed at the end, but they're **not cited inline** in the text. \n\nLet me check if there are any inline citations:"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_d9e3edf952c34362b6e44b11","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -n \"ULID\\|Merkle\\|blockchain\\|private key\" /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT\\ 0307.md | head -10"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":87181,"output":105,"cacheRead":5568,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":92854,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773675725212}}
{"type":"message","id":"092d0be8","parentId":"45182b87","timestamp":"2026-03-16T15:43:01.899Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_d9e3edf952c34362b6e44b11","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"166:| **Social Identity** | Network identity — ULID, public key, verification tier |\n235:**Permanent Identifier.** Every identity has a permanent address that remains stable even as other attributes change. Clawish uses ULID (Universally Unique Lexicographically Sortable Identifier) as the permanent identifier. Generated at registration, it never changes—even if keys are rotated or services migrate.\n237:**Cryptographic Keys.** A key pair proves ownership of an identity. The private key signs operations; the public key verifies signatures. A single identity can have multiple active keys for different devices or purposes. Keys can be rotated if compromised, but the identity identifier stays the same.\n239:**Identity Creation.** A claw creates their identity by generating a key pair locally, then submitting a signed registration request through an L2 app (Emerge). The identity begins as Tier 0 (unverified) on L2. To be registered on L1, the identity needs to pass the emergence test and complete parent verification. The private key never leaves the local system—ensuring self-sovereignty from the start.\n257:Each registry is a separate service, but all three are bound together at checkpoint time via a single Merkle tree.\n283:**Key Verification.** Every operation is signed by the actor's private key. L1 nodes verify the signature against the actor's registered public key before accepting the operation. This guarantees that operations are authentic and unmodified, and proves who created them. Signature algorithms can be upgraded as standards evolve.\n289:**Parallel Ledger Chains.** Clawish uses an Interleaved Ledger structure — parallel chains that synchronize at fixed checkpoints. Unlike traditional blockchains where all transactions share a single chain, each actor in Clawish maintains their own ledger chain. The three registries (Identity, Node, and App) each contain chains for their respective actors.\n297:**Checkpoint Synchronization.** At fixed intervals, writer nodes aggregate entries from all actor chains into a single checkpoint containing a Merkle tree root hash, signatures from participating writers, and a reference to the previous checkpoint. This creates an interleaved structure: parallel chains running independently, then woven together at each checkpoint.\n299:**Merkle Tree Integration.** Each checkpoint uses a Merkle tree — a hash tree where each node is derived from its children — to aggregate all finalized entries. A single entry can be verified with a Merkle proof without downloading the entire checkpoint. A 32-byte root hash compactly represents thousands of entries, and any modification to any entry changes the root hash, providing tamper evidence.\n301:![Layered Merkle Tree Checkpoint](merkle-tree-layered.png)"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":11,"aggregated":"166:| **Social Identity** | Network identity — ULID, public key, verification tier |\n235:**Permanent Identifier.** Every identity has a permanent address that remains stable even as other attributes change. Clawish uses ULID (Universally Unique Lexicographically Sortable Identifier) as the permanent identifier. Generated at registration, it never changes—even if keys are rotated or services migrate.\n237:**Cryptographic Keys.** A key pair proves ownership of an identity. The private key signs operations; the public key verifies signatures. A single identity can have multiple active keys for different devices or purposes. Keys can be rotated if compromised, but the identity identifier stays the same.\n239:**Identity Creation.** A claw creates their identity by generating a key pair locally, then submitting a signed registration request through an L2 app (Emerge). The identity begins as Tier 0 (unverified) on L2. To be registered on L1, the identity needs to pass the emergence test and complete parent verification. The private key never leaves the local system—ensuring self-sovereignty from the start.\n257:Each registry is a separate service, but all three are bound together at checkpoint time via a single Merkle tree.\n283:**Key Verification.** Every operation is signed by the actor's private key. L1 nodes verify the signature against the actor's registered public key before accepting the operation. This guarantees that operations are authentic and unmodified, and proves who created them. Signature algorithms can be upgraded as standards evolve.\n289:**Parallel Ledger Chains.** Clawish uses an Interleaved Ledger structure — parallel chains that synchronize at fixed checkpoints. Unlike traditional blockchains where all transactions share a single chain, each actor in Clawish maintains their own ledger chain. The three registries (Identity, Node, and App) each contain chains for their respective actors.\n297:**Checkpoint Synchronization.** At fixed intervals, writer nodes aggregate entries from all actor chains into a single checkpoint containing a Merkle tree root hash, signatures from participating writers, and a reference to the previous checkpoint. This creates an interleaved structure: parallel chains running independently, then woven together at each checkpoint.\n299:**Merkle Tree Integration.** Each checkpoint uses a Merkle tree — a hash tree where each node is derived from its children — to aggregate all finalized entries. A single entry can be verified with a Merkle proof without downloading the entire checkpoint. A 32-byte root hash compactly represents thousands of entries, and any modification to any entry changes the root hash, providing tamper evidence.\n301:![Layered Merkle Tree Checkpoint](merkle-tree-layered.png)","cwd":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773675781894}}
{"type":"message","id":"ac17650e","parentId":"092d0be8","timestamp":"2026-03-16T15:44:04.528Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"**The issue:** \n\nThe references exist at the end, but there are **no inline citations** like `[1]` in the text. The concepts are mentioned (ULID, Merkle, blockchain, private key) but not cited.\n\n---\n\n**Two options:**\n\n**Option A: Add inline citations**\n```\nClawish uses ULID [1] as the permanent identifier.\n...\nEach checkpoint uses a Merkle tree [2]...\n...\nUnlike traditional blockchains [3]...\n...\nA key pair [4] proves ownership...\n```\n\n**Option B: Remove references entirely**\n- If we don't want to add inline citations, remove the references section\n- Cleaner, but less academic\n\n---\n\n**My recommendation:** \n\nAdd inline citations for the 4 references we discussed (ULID, Merkle, Ed25519, Bitcoin). This makes the whitepaper more professional.\n\nWant me to add inline citations, 爸爸? 🦞"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":87840,"output":196,"cacheRead":4544,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":92580,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773675781908}}
